<TEXT>
an upcoming report by a un team 
investigating chemical weapons in the iraniraq war is largely a 
devastating account of iraqi atrocities diplomatic sources said 
a un team of military experts planned weekend talks in 
baghdad the iraqi capital to work out details for a ceasefire in 
the eightyear persian gulf war the team conducted talks in 
tehran the iranian capital this week 
a second team investigating the situation of prisoners of war 
was to leave tehran for baghdad over the weekend 
on friday secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar said he 
still was unable to bridge differences between iran and iraq over 
the issue of facetoface peace talks 
iraq demands direct talks with iran before accepting a 
ceasefire iran wants a ceasefire first 
the secretarygeneral said he expects more meetings with both 
sides today 
both sides still are interested in a solution of the 
problem he told reporters after meeting separately with envoys 
from the two countries at un headquarters in new york they 
have a divergence which is only normal 
saudi arabia a major supporter of iraq and financier of its war 
with iran has joined the ranks of nations trying to pressure 
baghdad to compromise and agree to an immediate ceasefire 
diplomatic sources said today 
prince bandar bin sultan bin abdul aziz saudia arabias us 
ambassador met privately with iraqi foreign minister tariq aziz 
and perez de cuellar on friday diplomatic sources speaking on 
condition of anonymity said the prince a member of the saudi 
royal family was trying to persuade iraq to drop its insistence on 
facetoface talks with iran before a ceasefire is declared 
the chemical weapons report detailing iraqs extensive use of 
the outlawed weapons is to be released monday diplomatic sources 
said on condition of anonymity they said the report would 
undermine iraqs position and mobilize international opinion 
against baghdad 
iraq has acknowleged the use of chemical weapons which are 
banned under the 1925 geneva convention but iraq contends iran 
introduced chemical weapons to the war 
in one of the latest claims of chemical warfare use irans 
islamic republic news agency today said iraqi forces chemically 
bombed a village just inside the border near the town of marivan in 
northwestern iran it said 10 civilians were injured 
after meeting friday with perez de cuellar foreign minister ali 
akbar velayati of iran said his country could consider direct talks 
with iraq after a ceasefire troop withdrawal and prisoner 
exchange he ruled out direct talks at this time 
tariq aziz later met the un chief for about 45 minutes and 
left without making a statement but middle east diplomats 
speaking on condition they not be identified said iraq had not 
softened its demand for direct talks 
perez de cuellar arranged the talks after iran announced last 
week after a years delay that it would accept a security council 
resolution calling for an immediate ceasefire and setting out a 
peace plan 
details of the secretarygenerals proposals to iran and iraq 
have not been disclosed 
velayati said iran considered the proposal in general to be 
positive would study it further and respond officially today 
perez de cuellar also said friday he was very hopeful that 
us marine lt col william r higgins would be released soon by 
his captors in lebanon 
the un security council adopted a resolution friday condemning 
the february kidnapping of higgins and demanding his immediate 
release 
higgins head of a un military observer group was kidnapped 
by proiranian extremists but the security council resolution did 
not mention his abductors or their sympathies 
perez de cuellar already has raised the higgins case with 
velayati and asked iran to use its influence with the kidnappers of 
higgins and other american and foreign hostages 
iran and iraq have been at war in the persian gulf since 
september 1980 with the loss of about a million lives 
</TEXT>
