<TEXT>
a nineday national festival spotlighting black 
artists opened saturday featuring a play by pulitizer prize winner 
charles fuller that examined the sometimes bitter experience of 
freedom for former slaves 
the world premiere of fullers latest effort sally took 
place friday night at the alliance theater in an unofficial 
kickoff to the first national black arts festival 
the festival formally began saturday with a parade through 
downtown atlanta an artists market a folk arts festival an 
african puppet show the second performance of sally and a 
production of sisters by atlanta playwright marsha jackson 
hundreds of thousands are expected to attend more than 100 
events showcasing black artists in eight disciplines theater 
folk arts dance film and video music visual arts literature 
and performance art 
sally produced by the negro ensemble company is the first 
of a fivepart series that fuller is planning on the slaves 
introduction to freedom fuller has worked with the company before 
their most noted collaboration was a soldiers play which won 
the pulitzer prize in 1982 
sally centers on a black regiment of the union army 
stationed in beaufort sc during the civil war the soldiers 
runaway slaves initially are attracted to the yankees by the 
promise of freedom but they soon learn that freedom will not bring 
equality 
a recurring theme of the play is the soldiers pay it is 10 a 
month for white soliders but congress cuts the blacks to 7 
the inequity causes them to ask if a black mans life is worth 
less than that of a white and leads the plays male lead sgt 
prince logan to make an agonizing choice between whether to stick 
with his angry men or with a general who wants to impress 
washington with a show of unity 
but the unity has long been broken by the pay issue one black 
soldier vendross played by ol duke screams at his comrades 
the only difference between slave and free is pay niggers 
douglas turner ward a cofounder of the negro ensemble company 
who directed sally and also plays the role of prince said his 
focus lately has been solely on the play despite his involvement 
in organizing the festival 
ward said he expects sally and one of the next installments 
in the series to debut in new york later this year he expects to 
be off stage by then 
i really consider myself pinchhitting as an actor i dont 
consider my performance as a pinchhitting performance but my 
intention is as we add the second play im going to try someone 
else as prince he said 
ward said one of the main attractions of sally to him was 
its portrayal of the different ways that people approached their 
freedom 
the interesting thing about the play is for the slaves its 
their first taste of freedom ward said they know what slavery 
is but they dont know what freedom is except theoretically and 
thats what this play captures the complexity of responses 
sally was warmly received by about 600 people who attended 
the opening night performance at the 800seat theater 
