recently called for reactivation of the international commission to 
verify progress of the plan 
ortega said his fellow central american presidents were 
unqualified to judge the plans progress because they themselves 
had failed to live up to it 
the plan was conceived and promoted by president oscar arias of 
costa rica who in december won the nobel peace prize for the idea 
the arias plan sets deadlines for compliance with negotiated 
ceasefires amnesties democratization an end to outside aid to 
insurgents and the use of one countrys territory by rebels from 
neighboring nations all were to be defined and achieved by nov 7 
1987 a date that came and went with only minimal compliance 
arias who once said he would be the first to condemn those who 
did not adhere to the deadlines said in january that the peace 
process should not be measured by a calendar 
in the months after it was signed the plan did bring some hopes 
of peace in the region but the hopes were quickly stilled by 
events 
the governments of el salvador and guatemala conducted talks 
with leaders of their leftist guerrilla movements but no progress 
resulted 
the honduran government claimed contra camps did not exist 
inside its territory and that it had no armed opposition an 
attitude sharply challenged by recent terrorist attacks on us 
servicemen stationed in that country 
nicaragua allowed the reopening of the opposition newspaper la 
prensa and a roman catholic radio station freed some of its 
political prisoners lifted the national state of emergency and 
began talks with the contras something the sandinistas said they 
would never do 
but the talks which broke down in early june produced only a 
temporary frequently broken ceasefire that has been extended 
through august the two sides remain at an impasse on the question 
of a permanent peace in their 7yearold civil war 
the sandinistas say they cannot support greater democracy until 
the contras lay down their arms and rejoin nicaraguan society but 
the rebels insist democracy must be instituted in nicaragua before 
they will give up fighting 
in the meantime both sides have hardened their positions 
the contras elected a new more conservative leadership to guide 
them the sandinistas closed the catholic radio station 
indefinitely and shut down la prensa for 15 days they also jailed 
dozens of contra leaders while expelling us ambassador richard 
melton and seven other american diplomats 
